00:22:26.030 --> 00:22:30.430
Talk a little bit about that?

00:22:30.430 --> 00:22:32.220
&gt;&gt; James Gleick: We're kind of
going back to the beginning again.

00:22:32.220 --> 00:22:37.730
We're going back to H.G.
Wells, because in 1895,

00:22:37.730 --> 00:22:44.340
H.G. Wells starts his
story in this way.

00:22:44.340 --> 00:22:49.480
His, not as narrator, but his
hero who doesn't even have a name

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:53.250
in the book is called, the
Time Traveller, gathers his--

00:22:53.250 --> 00:22:55.970
it's such an old fashion
way of writing.

00:22:55.970 --> 00:23:00.090
He's in his house in London and
he gathers his friends around

00:23:00.090 --> 00:23:03.030
and he says, "I've had a little
adventure and I'm going to tell you

00:23:03.030 --> 00:23:05.900
about it but first, I have to
explain a few things to you,"

00:23:05.900 --> 00:23:08.880
